Causes of hyperthyroidism


4. and thyroiditis

[!TIP] Mnemonic:
Single nodule, multiple nodules or Grave's.

Overview of evaluation of hyperthyroidism

  • Grave's disease is diagnosed based on classical clinical findings and history; if these are absent, other diagnoses are checked for.
  • Second line investigation is radioiodine uptake.

[!INFO] What is T3-thyrotoxicosis and T4 thyrotoxicosis

  • ⬇TSH, normal T4 and ⬆T3 = T3 thyrotoxicosis. Patients are clinically hyperthyroid. Tends to be the presentation early on in disease course.
  • ⬇ TSH, ⬆ T4 and normal T3 = T4 thyrotoxicosis. Can happen when a patient has a nonthyroidal illness which decreases peripheral T4 -> T3 conversion; but patient is still clinically hyperthyroid.
  • Disease follows a relapsing remitting course. Majority have recurrences.
  • Orbitopathy and pretibial myxoedema are not related to thyroxine levels. Orbitopathy does not correlate with disease activity.
  • Dermopathy
    • Pretibial myxoedema is caused by deposition of glycosaminoglycans (also known as mucopolysaccharides) and T cell infiltration.
  • Acropachy - a form of clubbing seen in Grave's disease; strongly associated with dermopathy.

4 Features of Grave's ophthalmopathy: (Harrison's)

  1. Lid retraction
  2. Periorbital oedema
  3. Conjunctival injection
  4. Proptosis
  5. and diplopia -> can occur late due to fibrosis of extraocular muscles.

As above, lid retraction is more suggestive of Grave's ophthalmopathy.
"Lid retraction (which causes a staring appearance) can occur in any form of thyrotoxicosis".

[!TIP] Summary

  • (low / nl TSH) + (low T4, T3, FT4) + (high rT3)
  • Occurs in ill / critically ill patients.
  • It may be that TSH is physiologically lowered to prevent a catabolic state.
  • In general, thyroid functions should not be done in critically ill patients because results can be misleading.
  • Replacement of thyroxine is not helpful in sick euthyroid symdrome. Management is to treat the underlying disease process.
  • Atropine - End point of treatment is
    • resolution of bronchoconstriction and clearing of respriatory secretions. (NOT THE APPEARANCE OF TACHYCARDIA AND MYDRIASIS as these can be caused by intrinsic sympathetic stimulation.
  • Seizure treatment: Benzodiazepines.
  • Succinylcholine(aka suxamethonium) (a short acting, depolarizing neuromuscular blocker) which works by blocking acetylcholine action, should be avoided because it can cause prolonged paralysis.

Succinylcholine and blockers

  • Succinylcholine is the only depolarizing blocker in use.
  • aka Suxamethonium
  • Chemically, it's made up of two ACh molecules bound together.
  • Suxa is resistant to hydrolysis by acetylcholinesterase.
  • Therefore, it causes prolonged stimulation of the nicotinic receptors.
    • Therefore, also affects the function of the autonomic nervous system.
  • Initial simulation causes fasciculations.
  • Following which there is muscle flaccidity.

[!INFO] voltage gated sodium channel function

the t gate closes after a fixed time following v gate opening. (i.e it's a time dependent gate) and then stays closed until the membrane repolarizes.
